From: Dustin Kirkland <dustin.kirkland@chainguard.dev>
Subject: [PATCH] Replace strlcpy() with snprintf() for portability

strlcpy() is not available in all C library versions (added to glibc in
2.38, and musl exposes it only under _GNU_SOURCE/_BSD_SOURCE which may
not be set). Replace the single call site with snprintf(dst, size, "%s",
src) which has identical truncating-copy semantics, requires no feature-
test macros, and is C99-portable across all platforms.

--- a/imagick_file.c
+++ b/imagick_file.c
@@ -113,7 +113,7 @@
 	}

 	/* Take a copy of the original string */
-	strlcpy(file->filename, filename, MaxTextExtent);
+	snprintf(file->filename, MaxTextExtent, "%s", filename);
 	file->filename_len = filename_len;

 	/* Break the path into pieces */
